# create basic bar plot

df.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(xx, xx)) # change figure size
plt.xlabel('X Label') # add to x-label to the plot
plt.ylabel('Y Label') # add y-label to the plot
plt.title('Titel') # add title to the plot
plt.show()

# use annotate method of the scripting layer or the pyplot interface
plt.annotate(xx=xx,  
             xx=xx)

arguments for .annotate()
s: str, the text of annotation.
xy: Tuple specifying the (x,y) point to annotate (in this case, end point of arrow).
xytext: Tuple specifying the (x,y) point to place the text (in this case, start point of arrow).
xycoords: The coordinate system that xy is given in - 'data' uses the coordinate system of the object being annotated (default).
arrowprops: Takes a dictionary of properties to draw the arrow:
arrowstyle: Specifies the arrow style, '->' is standard arrow.
connectionstyle: Specifies the connection type. arc3 is a straight line.
color: Specifies color of arrow.
lw: Specifies the line width.

# use annota() to display text element
plt.annotate('Text to display',  # text to display
             xy=(xx, xx),  # start the text at at point 
             rotation=xx,  # based on trial and error to match the arrow
             va='bottom',  # want the text to be vertically 'bottom' aligned
             ha='left',  # want the text to be horizontally 'left' algned.
             )
